sublevels.theory:
By default, C executes code line-by-line. **Control Flow** statements allow you to alter this flow based on conditions.

The most basic condition is the **`if` statement**. If the condition inside the parentheses is True (non-zero), the code block executes. If False (0), it skips the block.
```c
if (score >= 50) {
    printf("You passed!");
}
```

You can add an **`else` statement** to execute code when the condition is False.
```c
if (score >= 50) {
    printf("Pass");
} else {
    printf("Fail");
}
```
For multiple conditions, you can chain them using **`else if`**.

When you have many explicit cases to check against a single integer or character variable, a **`switch` statement** is cleaner and often faster than a long chain of `else if`s.

```c
switch (grade) {
    case 'A':
        printf("Excellent");
        break;
    case 'B':
        printf("Good");
        break;
    default:
        printf("Unknown grade");
}
```

The **`break`** keyword is crucial! If you omit `break`, Execution will "fall through" into the next case, executing its code regardless of whether the condition matches. 

The **`default`** block is optional and acts like an `else` block—it catches anything that didn't match a defined `case`.

Beyond standard `if` and `switch`, C has a specialized (and highly discouraged) control flow mechanism: the **`goto` statement**.

`goto` performs an unconditional jump to a named label within the same function.
```c
    if (error_occurred) {
        goto cleanup;
    }
    // ... code ...
cleanup:
    free(memory);
```
While historically reviled for creating "spaghetti code", `goto` remains useful in Linux kernel code and complex C programs primarily for a single pattern: **Centralized Error Cleanup**, as C lacks modern `try/catch/finally` blocks.

Another advanced trick is intentionally using **switch fallthrough**: stacking cases without `break` when multiple cases should execute exactly the same code (e.g., matching multiple vowel characters to single output logic).
